04575nam a22007455i 9780823264407DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232644077 a10.1515/97808232644072doi  a(DE-B1597)555122  a(OCoLC)914229950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB105.L54bT47 2015 7aMUS0410002bisacsh04a128/.422300aThresholds of Listening :bSound, Technics, Space /cSander van Maas. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Auditory Re-Turn (The Point of Listening) -- t2. "Dear Listener . . .": Music and the Invention of Subjectivity -- t3. Scenes of Devastation: Interpellation, Finite and Infi nite -- t4. Positive Feedback: Listening behind Hearing -- t5. "Antennas Have Long Since Invaded Our Brains" -- t6. Movement at the Boundaries of Listening, Composition, and Performance -- t7. The Biopolitics of Noise: Kafka's "Der Bau" -- t8. Torture as an Instrument of Music -- t9. Stop It, I Like It! -- t10. Sounds of Belonging -- t11. Back to the Beat -- t12. The Discovery of Slowness in Music -- t13. Negotiating Ecstasy -- tNOTES -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThresholds of Listening addresses recent and historical changes in the ways listening has been conceived. Listening, having been emancipated from the passive, subjected position of reception, has come to be asserted as an active force in culture and in collective and individual politics.The contributors to this volume show that the exteriorization of listening- brought into relief by recent historical studies of technologies of listening-involves a re-negotiation of the theoretical and pragmatic distinctions that underpin the notion of listening. Focusing on the manifold borderlines between listening and its erstwhile others, such as speaking, reading, touching, seeing, or hearing, the book maps new frontiers in the history of aurality. They suggest that listening's finitude- defined in some of the essays as its death or deadliness-should be considered as a heuristic instrument rather than as a mere descriptor.Listening emerges where it appears to end or to run up against thresholds and limits-or when it takes unexpected turns. Listening's recent emergence on the cultural and theoretical scene may therefore be productively read against contemporary recurrences of the motifs of elusiveness, finitude, and resistance to open up new politics, discourses, and technologies of aurality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aListening (Philosophy) 0aListening (Philosophy). 4aaddress. 4aaurality'. 4ahearing technology. 4aliminal. 4alistening. 4asenses. 4atropes. 7aMUSIC / Instruction & Study / Theory.2bisacsh1 aMaas, Sander van, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823264407zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823264407423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823264407.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK